"Takayabu I., Kato H., Nishizawa K., Takayabu Y.N., Sato Y., Sasaki H., Kurihara K., Kitoh A.","Future projections in precipitation over Asia simulated by two RCMs nested into MRI-CGCM2.2",2007,"Journal of the Meteorological Society of Japan","85","4",,"511","519",,,10.2151/jmsj.85.511,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-35348963058&partnerID=40&md5=84cc02704ab3cb747adc580e7ce77af7","Meteorological Research Institute, 1-1 Nagamine, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-0052, Japan; Central Research Institute of Electric Power Industry, Tokyo, Japan; Central of Climate System Research, University of Tokyo, Kashiwa, Japan","Takayabu, I., Meteorological Research Institute, 1-1 Nagamine, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-0052, Japan; Kato, H., Central Research Institute of Electric Power Industry, Tokyo, Japan; Nishizawa, K., Central Research Institute of Electric Power Industry, Tokyo, Japan; Takayabu, Y.N., Central of Climate System Research, University of Tokyo, Kashiwa, Japan; Sato, Y., Meteorological Research Institute, 1-1 Nagamine, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-0052, Japan; Sasaki, H., Meteorological Research Institute, 1-1 Nagamine, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-0052, Japan; Kurihara, K., Meteorological Research Institute, 1-1 Nagamine, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-0052, Japan; Kitoh, A., Meteorological Research Institute, 1-1 Nagamine, Tsukuba, Ibaraki 305-0052, Japan","We statistically analyzed both the reproducibility of the present climate, and future climate projections in the Asian monsoon region, using two Regional Climate Models (RCMs), nested into the MRI-CGCM2.2 to assess regional climate projections associated with global warming. Both GCM-RCM systems reproduced the present regional surface air temperature well. Also, they indicated about the same temperature increases as that of GCM for all regions over the Asian continent. The reproducibility of the present-climate precipitation amounts, in the lower-latitude regions was not as good as that of the surface air temperature, although it was better simulated in the higher-latitude regions. The future precipitation increase was not statistically significant. It was also statistically revealed that precipitation in future projections, with GCM-RCM systems, tended to converge in regions where the model biases were small. This result suggests the importance of an accurate reproduction of the present regional climate using physically based dynamical models, in order to analyze regional climate changes. © 2007, Meteorological Society of Japan.",,"air temperature; climate change; general circulation model; global warming; regional climate; Asia; Eurasia",,,,,,"Adler, R.F., Huffman, G.J., Chang, A., Ferrano, R., Xie, P.-P., Janowiac, J., Rudolf, B., Nelkin, E., The version-2 Global Precipitation Climatology Project (GPCP) Monthly Precipitation Analysis (1979 Present) (2003) J. Hydrometeor, 4, pp. 1147-1167; Anthes, R.A., A cumulus parameterization scheme utilizing a one-dimensional cloud model (1977) Mon. Wea. Rev, 105, pp. 270-286; Anthes, R.A., Hsie, E.-Y., Kuo, Y.-H., (1987) Description of the Penn State/NCAR Mesoscale Model version 4 (MM4), , NCAR Technical Note. NCAR/TN-282+STR, 66 pp; Arakawa, A., Schubert, W.H., Interactions of cumulus cloud ensemble with the large-scale environment. Part I (1974) J. Atmos. Sci, 31, pp. 671-701; Benwell, G.R.R., Bushby, F.H., A case study of frontal behavior using a 10-level primitive equation model (1970) Quart. J. Roy. Meteor. Soc, 96, pp. 287-296; Bhaskaran, B., Jones, R.G., Murphy, J.M., Noguer, M., Simulations of the Indian summer monsoon using a nested regional climate model: Domain size experiments (1996) Clim. Dyn, 12, pp. 573-587; Bonan, G.B, 1996: The NCAR land surface model (LSM version 1.0) coupled to the NCAR Community Climate Model. NCAR Technical Note, NCAR/ TN-282+STR, 66 ppChristensen, J.H., Machenhauer, B., Jones, R.G., Schaer, C., Ruti, P.M., Castro, M., Visconti, G., Validation of present-day regional climate simulations over Europe: LAM simulations w